The Eckener Alternative
by James L. Cambias

The Hindenburg swung gently on the mast at Lakehurst as the sky over New  Jersey turned to purple twilight.nbsp; All the passengers, the reporters,  the newsreel men were gone.nbsp; A couple of sailors stood guard beneath the  big ship to enforce the no-smoking rule.

John Cavalli waited until the watchman below had turned away,  then slid down the stern rope to the ground.nbsp; He hunkered down next to  the big rolling anchor weight for a couple of minutes, then hurried off  into the darkness beyond the floodlights.

Once he was clear, Cavalli stopped to peel off the Russian army  arctic commando suit he'd been wearing ever since the Zeppelin had  lifted off from Frankfurt-am-Main.nbsp; It had kept him warm as he hid among  the gas cells with his IR goggles and fire extinguisher, but now in the  warmth of a spring evening it was stifling.

He hit the RETURN button on his wristband and disappeared.

#

"You can't make big changes," said the instructor the first day of Temporal Studies class.nbsp; He was a very laid-back physicist recruited from California in 2020s.nbsp; "That's the most important rule.nbsp; The folks we  work for are the result of a particular set of historical events.nbsp;Change history too much and their probability level drops below 50  percent.nbsp; If that happens, all this" -- his gesture encompassed the Time  Center -- goes away and we're out of a job.nbsp; If we even exist anymore."

A student in the row ahead of Cavalli raised his hand.nbsp; "What about making little changes?"

"Little  changes are fine.nbsp; We make little changes all the time.nbsp; Most of them  are things like making long-term investments, buying up art treasures  for safekeeping, keeping species from going extinct, that kind of  thing.nbsp; You're going to learn all about gauging the effect of changes,  avoiding heterodynes and chaotic points, and when it's okay to step on  butterflies."

Cavalli was listening, but in the margin of his notebook he was doodling airships.

#

The  timegate stage was dark and the control room was empty, just as he'd  left it.nbsp; The Coke can was still on the console.nbsp; Was it maybe a little  further to the left than he remembered?nbsp; He stepped off the stage and  took a drink.nbsp; Still tasted the same.nbsp; It would take a pretty big  timeshift to change the flavor of Coca-Cola.

Cavalli locked the door behind him with his purloined master key  (the Time Center used mechanical locks because they were a bit more  resistant to minor time-shifts) and headed for the library.nbsp; He found a  book about Zeppelins he didn't remember and skimmed the pages.nbsp; Hindenburg served safely until 1939; scrapped when WWII broke out.nbsp; No  postwar Zeppelins.nbsp; The usual "return of the airship" speculations.

Damn.nbsp; It hadn't worked.nbsp; He had hoped erasing the vivid image  of the Hindenburg fire would have been enough to keep passenger  airships alive, but the war still marked the end of their era.

#

"So why don't we stop things like the Holocaust or the firebombing of  Dresden?"nbsp; It was a relatively quiet dorm room party with half a dozen  trainees blowing off steam after the first written exam.nbsp; Cavalli didn't  see who asked the question, but he sounded drunk.

Anna Kyle, the third-year trainee, answered. "Too big.nbsp; The  models predict major shifts in the 21st Century if there's no  Holocaust.nbsp; You lose the Cold War and the whole Jihad era.nbsp; We just stay  away from World War II if we can help it.nbsp; Rescue a few things from  museums before they get flattened, take some videos for historians,  that's all."

